<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=100750501830854></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100750501830854><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=5&mid=100750501830854>RE: Feign Death</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=5&mid=100750501830854#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=61489><span id=Scholar>Kamlatir, Eater of Souls</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>66 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Dec 4th 5:30 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.85]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I've posted about feign death in another thread, can't really recall where right now though so I'll recap some of my points. Always click of attack before fegning. Trying to fool mobs into thinking you are dead while attacking them is a doomed venture, you'll only have alot of unsucessful attempts and that usually hurts alot.<br><br>Unlike the monks our fd is a spell and it comes fully stocked with all the disadvantages of spells. First off you have a casting time and secondly you run the chance of being interrupted. Now, this leads to sort of a level dependancy in the shadowknights fd. Basically, you can probably feign up to about three blue mobs or even more in some cases but it's a game of chance trying to feign two red ones, and not with very good odds at that. Reason for this is two red mobs will hit you alot, pushing you back a good ways and increasing the chance of an interrupt in the casting. Blue mobs usually don't hit you that much and not with the same amount of movement. I have an amusing little anekdote from SG where our monks had called it a night and I was the only fd'er left in the party. We were facing two of the seahorses and wanted to split them since we weren't exactly full force ( if you've fought these creatures you know what I mean, they hit hard and fast ). Being somewhat experienced with fd at that time I offered to try and split them, knowing full well that I was basically comitting suicide. They were indeed red but I aggroed them and proceeded to trying to fd. It was really quite amusing when I woke up in Kael and scrolled up to see what the hell happened. First 4 lines were red damage lines. Then came <br><br>You begin casting... <br>You are interrupted... <br>6 red damage lines... <br>You begin casting...<br>8 red damage lines...<br>You are interrupted...<br>4 red damage lines...<br>LOADING...<br><br>The horsies split very nicely but you could've sent in a level 30 wizard and achieved the same results =) For a monk this would never have been a problem, their fd is instantanious. On the other hand I've pulled KC with no problems at all, fd splitting up to 4 blues ( what can I say, the trains in there are horrendus ). Going above a certain number of blues will also spell certain death. I'll never forget the time we were returning from ghost of Kindle in The Hole and my ivu dropped. I had about seven or eight mobs on me and I only managed to attempt to fd once since I was stunned the entire time until loading message. Same thing here, for monks it doesn't matter if there are three of eight mobs, feign is instant and I've gotten the impression that the act is stacked for monks, meaning that if you feign while stunned the actual fd will come as soon as you're unstunned. Another thing about red mobs is that you usually only have one chance of feigning due to the long recast time. If you fail and are facing two or three red mobs chances are that you're dead before that gem pops again. Pulling multiple casters is also a tricky business. Trying to time the feign becomes close to impossible if you have three fast throwing casters ( Chardok comes to mind ).<br><br>About aggro of level 35+ mobs. Yes, they will have a hard time of forgetting you after you've feigned. The chance of a wipe of the hate list is however greatly increased if the mob returns to it's spawnpoint before you stand up. Another method of loosing the aggro is waiting until you can cast again and then quickly stand up and feign a second time ( followed by additional times until your sure you're in the clear ). Every feign will increase the chance of you being removed from that hateful aggro list.<br><br>It may sound as I am disregarding feign death as a useful ability for the shadowknight but nothing could be more wrong. The shadowknight is an excellent tagger among other things. Tagging being the tactic where you feign in a predesignated spot and a monk puller brings a bunch of mobs to that spot, feigns and then you take one or two of them back to the group. Feign death will save you many times through your gaming career, running through higher level zones and picking up some aggro along the way. If you happen to overdo the main tank in a raid with an unfortunate spell all you need to do is fd and the aggro will be back on him in a flash.<br><br>To summarize:<br>Always turn off attack.<br>Pick your battles carefully, even when pulling blues it's not wise to overdo it.<br>Multiple reds means you better be damn sure you succeed in your feign.<br>Multiple casters means trouble ( most often four spells death )<br>Level 35+ aggro is tricky, mobs returning to spawn point and multiple feigns will greatly increase your chance of a successful fd.<br><br>I'm very interested in seeing if the improved feign death changes any of the above. Received at level 60 it has a one second casting time and only four seconds recast time. It may make a difference, it may not. After all, the mobs you're fighting level up too =)<br><br>Kamlatir Baresi,<br>54 Reaver, <br>The Rathe<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
